device in a lanyard like this
or perhaps in a shirt pocket.

00:15:07.160 --> 00:15:10.580
Now, this is a big objective of
ours, this passive experience.

00:15:10.580 --> 00:15:13.010
We don't want to force the
user to interrupt the activity

00:15:13.010 --> 00:15:14.430
they're engaging with.

00:15:14.430 --> 00:15:16.580
For example, if the
user is cooking,

00:15:16.580 --> 00:15:18.890
they can remain engaged
in that activity

00:15:18.890 --> 00:15:20.930
without having to
take out their device

00:15:20.930 --> 00:15:23.320
and interact with the screen.

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:25.870
So while wearing
the phone, Lookout

00:15:25.870 --> 00:15:29.140
provides these useful hints
about what the user is holding

00:15:29.140 --> 00:15:32.110
in front of them, and
to facilitate this,

00:15:32.110 --> 00:15:34.840
we've designed a set
of external controls.

00:15:34.840 --> 00:15:36.940
So as you may have
noticed in the video,

00:15:36.940 --> 00:15:38.740
a user can actually
knock on the device

00:15:38.740 --> 00:15:41.350
to begin the recognition, this
live recognition that Lookout

00:15:41.350 --> 00:15:42.342
provides.

00:15:42.342 --> 00:15:44.800
And they can do other things
like cover the camera to pause

00:15:44.800 --> 00:15:47.542
recognition or use
the fingerprint sensor

00:15:47.542 --> 00:15:48.625
to change different modes.

00:15:52.280 --> 00:15:55.070
So let me tell you a little
bit about how this works.

00:15:55.070 --> 00:15:58.180
So first, Lookout will collect
live imagery of the scene

00:15:58.180 --> 00:16:00.580
around the user,
and then we'll run

00:16:00.580 --> 00:16:03.220
a series of machine
learning recognizers

00:16:03.220 --> 00:16:07.350
to detect things like barcodes,
detect if people are present,

00:16:07.350 --> 00:16:11.250
detect objects, and
read text in the scene.

00:16:11.250 --> 00:16:14.520
The next thing we do is
score these items, first

00:16:14.520 --> 00:16:17.320
based on a personalization
model and the mode

00:16:17.320 --> 00:16:19.170
that the user has chosen.

00:16:19.170 --> 00:16:21.750
This way, we only speak the
relevant and important items

00:16:21.750 --> 00:16:22.806
to the user.

00:16:22.806 --> 00:16:24.180
This is important
because, as you

00:16:24.180 --> 00:16:25.800
can imagine, in
a standard scene,

00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:27.900
there could be many
things we want to--

00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:29.250
we can detect.

00:16:29.250 --> 00:16:30.960
However, we only
want to tell the user

00:16:30.960 --> 00:16:33.000
about the important
things based on what

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:37.220
we know about the context
that they're currently in.

00:16:37.220 --> 00:16:39.740
It's important to note
that we do most of this

00:16:39.740 --> 00:16:42.500
all on the device, so
that latency is low,

00:16:42.500 --> 00:16:44.450
and you can actually
use this app completely

00:16:44.450 --> 00:16:46.164
without an internet connection.

00:16:52.940 --> 00:16:55.430
So that's Lookout,
an app for users

00:16:55.430 --> 00:16:57.200
who are blind and
low vision that

00:16:57.200 --> 00:16:59.420
harnesses the power
of machine learning

00:16:59.420 --> 00:17:02.120
to provide relevant results
about physical spaces

00:17:02.120 --> 00:17:03.710
around them.

00:17:03.710 --> 00:17:06.560
It's coming to the Play Store
for users in the US on Pixel

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:10.130
devices very soon this summer.

00:17:10.130 --> 00:17:12.950
And we'll also start rolling
out to trusted testers,

00:17:12.950 --> 00:17:14.420
