00:19:35.710 --> 00:19:38.640
Now, I'm going to talk a
bit about Android framework,

00:19:38.640 --> 00:19:41.280
and our goal in the Android
Accessibility framework

00:19:41.280 --> 00:19:44.730
is to help get rid
of the assumptions

00:19:44.730 --> 00:19:46.890
that device are built on.

00:19:46.890 --> 00:19:50.790
For example, not all users can
interact with the touch screen

00:19:50.790 --> 00:19:53.970
or with the standard UI
or even hear the sounds

00:19:53.970 --> 00:19:56.010
that the device is producing.

00:19:56.010 --> 00:19:59.980
Now, we're supporting
this goal in two ways.

00:19:59.980 --> 00:20:02.200
The first one is
we're developing

00:20:02.200 --> 00:20:06.870
APIs for apps and services
to make it easier to support

00:20:06.870 --> 00:20:08.970
wide range of audience.

00:20:08.970 --> 00:20:11.850
And second, we are implementing
accessibility features

00:20:11.850 --> 00:20:13.190
into the framework.

00:20:15.830 --> 00:20:19.190
Now, I will talk about
three new API addition

00:20:19.190 --> 00:20:23.180
to enable developers to make
their app more accessible,

00:20:23.180 --> 00:20:26.690
and the first one
is add a pane title.

00:20:26.690 --> 00:20:30.390
So first, let me start
with, what is a pane?

00:20:30.390 --> 00:20:33.410
A pane is a section of the
window that these visually

00:20:33.410 --> 00:20:35.990
distinct for user with--

00:20:35.990 --> 00:20:37.790
which is visually
distinct for user,

00:20:37.790 --> 00:20:41.030
and change it like
a window changes.

00:20:41.030 --> 00:20:43.100
An example of the
pane, you can see here

00:20:43.100 --> 00:20:46.820
in the Quick Setting and
the notification shade.

00:20:46.820 --> 00:20:49.910
Prior to Android P,
Accessibility Services

00:20:49.910 --> 00:20:53.120
could not easily determined
when panes on the screen

00:20:53.120 --> 00:20:55.630
had been updated.

00:20:55.630 --> 00:20:59.120
In Android P, we added an
attribute called Accessibility

00:20:59.120 --> 00:21:00.430
Pane Title.

00:21:00.430 --> 00:21:03.350
Now, Accessibility
Services are automatically

00:21:03.350 --> 00:21:08.030
notified to changes
to the pane so user

00:21:08.030 --> 00:21:11.210
get more granular
information about what

00:21:11.210 --> 00:21:15.530
has changed with minimal
input from app developer.

00:21:15.530 --> 00:21:20.340
So please do add a
title to your pane.

00:21:20.340 --> 00:21:24.230
The second API is called
an Accessibility Heading.

00:21:24.230 --> 00:21:26.000
This is an attribute
so developer

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:30.750
can mark whether something is
a heading inside their app,

00:21:30.750 --> 00:21:36.050
and this is intended for
apps with text heavy views.

00:21:36.050 --> 00:21:38.870
This will allow TalkBack to a
user who cannot see the screen

00:21:38.870 --> 00:21:42.710
to navigate more efficiently
between different heading

00:21:42.710 --> 00:21:48.490
inside their app without force
listening to the whole text.

00:21:48.490 --> 00:21:51.870
And the last API is
we add the ability--

00:21:51.870 --> 00:21:58.500
we basically-- the last API is
for setting what is focusable,

00:21:58.500 --> 00:22:00.900
and that API is
designed to control

00:22:00.900 --> 00:22:04.740
the grouping of the content.

00:22:04.740 --> 00:22:07.950
For example, let's say that
you have sports scores,

00:22:07.950 --> 00:22:13.140
and you want to ensure that
the number goes with the team

00:22:13.140 --> 00:22:16.770
instead of TalkBack reading
all the teams and then all

00:22:16.770 --> 00:22:20.700
the numbers, which can be very
confusing for the users who

00:22:20.700 --> 00:22:22.470
cannot see the screen.

00:22:22.470 --> 00:22:25.470
Now, you can use
Screen Reader Focusable

00:22:25.470 --> 00:22:29.670
to improve how screen
readers group the content.

00:22:29.670 --> 00:22:33.060
And by the way, we're also
updating our documentation

00:22:33.060 --> 00:22:35.610
for Accessibility
Focus and Grouping,

00:22:35.610 --> 00:22:38.670
so please check it out,
the Accessibility Section

00:22:38.670 --> 00:22:40.275
in developer.android.com.

00:22:44.830 --> 00:22:48.040
Now, I'm going to talk about
three new additional features

00:22:48.040 --> 00:22:50.440
coming to the Android framework.

00:22:50.440 --> 00:22:53.690
The first one is
Adjust Vibration.

00:22:53.690 --> 00:22:58.630
This is a new setting for
users with dexterity issues

00:22:58.630 --> 00:23:02.620
to adjust the ringer
notification vibration and also

00:23:02.620 --> 00:23:05.470
the touch sensitivity.

00:23:05.470 --> 00:23:10.240
The second setting is
called Remove Animation,

00:23:10.240 --> 00:23:14.200
as some users find
animation distracting,

00:23:14.200 --> 00:23:19.820
so we basically just added a
new setting to turn those off.

00:23:19.820 --> 00:23:28.210
And the last feature is, a year
ago, we launched the Volume Key

00:23:28.210 --> 00:23:29.860
Accessibility Shortcut.

00:23:29.860 --> 00:23:35.110
So basically, to toggle on and
off Accessibility Services,

00:23:35.110 --> 00:23:39.760
you need to long press, for
three seconds, the volume keys.

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:43.220
Now, we did two changes to
that one based on the feedback.

00:23:43.220 --> 00:23:45.130
The first one, we
added new setting

00:23:45.130 --> 00:23:47.440
that you can toggle
on and off, which

00:23:47.440 --> 00:23:50.170
is Color Correction
and Coloring Version.

00:23:50.170 --> 00:23:52.660
And the second one is
we reduced the time

00:23:52.660 --> 00:23:56.170
to activate from three
seconds to one second

00:23:56.170 --> 00:23:58.560
after the initial activation.

00:24:05.550 --> 00:24:07.350
In the next section,
I'm going to talk

00:24:07.350 --> 00:24:10.800
about testing for accessibility
and its importance

00:24:10.800 --> 00:24:14.870
for everything that
we build into the OS.

00:24:14.870 --> 00:24:18.150
We see the power of the
Accessibility Services

00:24:18.150 --> 00:24:21.450
in the app ecosystem, and
we want that ecosystem to be

00:24:21.450 --> 00:24:23.235
as accessible as possible.

00:24:25.850 --> 00:24:29.460
Now, there are multiple ways to
test including manual testing

00:24:29.460 --> 00:24:31.170
and automated testing.

00:24:31.170 --> 00:24:33.810
In general, we found
the combination of both

00:24:33.810 --> 00:24:36.990
could provide you a better
coverage for your app.

00:24:36.990 --> 00:24:39.570
Next, I'm going to cover
different testing tools

00:24:39.570 --> 00:24:44.250
and how those can be integrated
to cover accessibility--

00:24:44.250 --> 00:24:46.020
to discover
accessibility issues.

00:24:49.980 --> 00:24:54.180
First, let me talk a little
bit about manual testing.

00:24:54.180 --> 00:24:57.240
This is the most reliable
way to understand

00:24:57.240 --> 00:25:01.230
how your products are
used by different users

00:25:01.230 --> 00:25:03.300
with disabilities.

00:25:03.300 --> 00:25:07.740
What you need there is you
need to turn on TalkBack

00:25:07.740 --> 00:25:11.010
or Switch Access with
your app because you

00:25:11.010 --> 00:25:14.370
want to be in the
shoes of the user

00:25:14.370 --> 00:25:18.400
to feel how it is to run
an Accessibility Service.

00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:22.110
However, we are aware that
manual testing takes time,

00:25:22.110 --> 00:25:25.260
and you cannot test for
every change that you make

00:25:25.260 --> 00:25:28.500
into the app, and for
that, we also provide--

00:25:28.500 --> 00:25:30.055
there is also automated testing.

00:25:33.510 --> 00:25:36.840
We develop Android
Accessibility Testing Framework,

00:25:36.840 --> 00:25:41.310
also shortly called
ATF, to quickly identify

00:25:41.310 --> 00:25:46.560
common accessibility issues
early in the development cycle.

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:50.100
ATF is an open source
library, which we already

00:25:50.100 --> 00:25:55.500
integrated into Espresso and
Roboelectric Testing Framework

00:25:55.500 --> 00:25:58.410
so you can leverage your
existing test to identify

00:25:58.410 --> 00:26:01.280
accessibility issues.

00:26:01.280 --> 00:26:07.410
ATF 3.0 is now
available on GitHub.

00:26:07.410 --> 00:26:10.080
Next, we have two
automated tools

00:26:10.080 --> 00:26:13.290
that integrate Accessibility
Testing Framework--

00:26:13.290 --> 00:26:16.640
Play Pre-Launch Report
and Accessibility Scanner.

00:26:20.700 --> 00:26:25.680
In Play Pre-Launch Report,
we're making it even easier

00:26:25.680 --> 00:26:27.570
to get accessibility
tests resolved

00:26:27.570 --> 00:26:33.260
by integrating those directly
into the developer console.

00:26:33.260 --> 00:26:36.450
Now, first, what is
Play Pre-Launch Report?

00:26:36.450 --> 00:26:39.810
This is an automated
testing solution,

00:26:39.810 --> 00:26:43.470
which calls apps on
multiple physical devices

00:26:43.470 --> 00:26:46.860
and detects issues the developer
can fix before reaching

00:26:46.860 --> 00:26:50.280
their end users,
including recognizing

00:26:50.280 --> 00:26:53.820
crashes and performance issues.

00:26:53.820 --> 00:26:56.860
The tool runs automatically
on all APK published

00:26:56.860 --> 00:26:59.580
to the alpha and beta channel.

00:26:59.580 --> 00:27:01.980
Now, Play Pre-Launch--

00:27:01.980 --> 00:27:06.255
Play Pre-Launch Report also
include accessibility tests.

00:27:09.910 --> 00:27:12.940
This is yet another
example how we

00:27:12.940 --> 00:27:17.020
integrate our core
accessibility testing library.

00:27:17.020 --> 00:27:21.010
As Play Pre-Launch Report calls
your app, as in this example--

00:27:21.010 --> 00:27:22.750
this is a cooking app.

00:27:22.750 --> 00:27:26.740
In each step, it will launch
accessibility tests including

00:27:26.740 --> 00:27:30.490
contrast ratio, touch target
size, missing labels, and so

00:27:30.490 --> 00:27:31.090
on.

00:27:31.090 --> 00:27:33.670
And the test result will
be automatically integrated

00:27:33.670 --> 00:27:35.560
into the test report.

00:27:35.560 --> 00:27:40.030
This will provide the developer
an opportunity to fix those--

00:27:40.030 --> 00:27:42.250
to fix those before their
app launches and make

00:27:42.250 --> 00:27:44.770
their app more accessible.

00:27:47.710 --> 00:27:51.520
Lastly, I'll mention
Accessibility Scanner,

00:27:51.520 --> 00:27:54.610
which is an app that suggests
accessibility improvement

00:27:54.610 --> 00:27:58.360
for Android apps utilizing
Accessibility Testing

00:27:58.360 --> 00:27:59.620
Framework.

00:27:59.620 --> 00:28:03.730
And we're very happy
that up until today,

00:28:03.730 --> 00:28:07.260
Accessibility Scanner
discovered more than three

00:28:07.260 --> 00:28:11.370
and a half million opportunities
for improving accessibility

00:28:11.370 --> 00:28:12.970
in apps--

00:28:12.970 --> 00:28:15.150
for improving
accessibility apps.

00:28:15.150 --> 00:28:17.820
So big shout out for
Accessibility Scanner.

00:28:21.410 --> 00:28:23.930
A new version of
Accessibility Scanner

00:28:23.930 --> 00:28:27.710
is available today with
additional accessibility

00:28:27.710 --> 00:28:31.100
checks, such as Traversal
Order for Screenwriter,

00:28:31.100 --> 00:28:34.130
an inferent element
for accessibility.

00:28:34.130 --> 00:28:37.430
We also improve the UI
for contrast suggestion.

00:28:37.430 --> 00:28:41.780
And finally, we also are
allowing changes for threshold

00:28:41.780 --> 00:28:45.120
for contrast ratio
and touch target size.

00:28:45.120 --> 00:28:47.210
So to download
Accessibility Scanner,

00:28:47.210 --> 00:28:52.150
please go to
g.co/accessibilityscanner.

00:28:52.150 --> 00:28:55.670
To sum up this section, we
talked about manual testing,

00:28:55.670 --> 00:28:59.810
and we showed a number of
tools to help automate testing.

00:28:59.810 --> 00:29:04.580
But the most successful projects
incorporate both manual testing

00:29:04.580 --> 00:29:06.950
and automated
testing, so please,

00:29:06.950 --> 00:29:09.800
do try out the
different tools and do

00:29:09.800 --> 00:29:14.870
develop a testing strategy for
accessibility for your app.

00:29:14.870 --> 00:29:16.880
Now, another vital
piece of the puzzle

00:29:16.880 --> 00:29:19.340
is to understand
the user experience

00:29:19.340 --> 00:29:22.080
and your user needs,
and with that said,

00:29:22.080 --> 00:29:25.190
I will hand it off to Melissa
to talk about user research.

00:29:30.884 --> 00:29:32.300
MELISSA BARNHART:
Thank you, Maya.

00:29:32.300 --> 00:29:35.400
My name's Melissa Barnhart,
and I'm a user experience

00:29:35.400 --> 00:29:37.110
researcher on Android.

00:29:37.110 --> 00:29:39.180
So now that we've
gotten a sneak peek

00:29:39.180 --> 00:29:42.790
at the accessibility features
and services coming in Android

00:29:42.790 --> 00:29:45.000
P, I'd like to
talk about the role

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:48.240
of user research and the
design and development process.

00:29:51.270 --> 00:29:54.840
But first, what exactly
is user research?

00:29:54.840 --> 00:29:59.070
User research focuses on
understanding user behaviors,

00:29:59.070 --> 00:30:01.050
needs, and motivations.

00:30:01.050 --> 00:30:03.990
It is the process of
understanding the impact

00:30:03.990 --> 00:30:05.385
of design on an audience.

00:30:08.470 --> 00:30:12.100
So as technologists, we may
think we know what's best

00:30:12.100 --> 00:30:14.860
for our users, but
oftentimes, we don't.

00:30:14.860 --> 00:30:18.760
The user is truly the
expert in their experiences.

00:30:18.760 --> 00:30:21.760
By seeking to understand
user behaviors, needs,

00:30:21.760 --> 00:30:25.270
and motivations, we start
to challenge our assumptions

00:30:25.270 --> 00:30:27.160
and reshape our perspectives.

00:30:29.950 --> 00:30:30.910
Why do it?

00:30:30.910 --> 00:30:33.190
Why do we do user research?

00:30:33.190 --> 00:30:36.940
You may have heard the stat that
nine out of 10 startups fail,

00:30:36.940 --> 00:30:40.450
but you may not know that the
number one reason for failure

00:30:40.450 --> 00:30:43.580
is lack of a market
need for a product.

00:30:43.580 --> 00:30:47.710
So in those situations, people
design and develop products,

00:30:47.710 --> 00:30:49.570
then look for an
audience who might

00:30:49.570 --> 00:30:51.580
be interested in using them.

00:30:51.580 --> 00:30:54.730
User research advocates
for the opposite.

00:30:54.730 --> 00:30:58.810
By putting users first,
you can validate your ideas

00:30:58.810 --> 00:31:00.700
and inform your
product's direction.

00:31:04.290 --> 00:31:07.190
Hopefully, you're thinking,
great, but when do I get

00:31:07.190 --> 00:31:07.910
started?

00:31:07.910 --> 00:31:10.600
And the short answer is now.

00:31:10.600 --> 00:31:13.190
User research involves
a set of practices

00:31:13.190 --> 00:31:17.000
that runs along your existing
product development cycle,

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.010
helping you make
decisions at each stage.

00:31:20.010 --> 00:31:23.000
So methods like field
studies, interviews,

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:25.220
or competitive
analysis can help you

00:31:25.220 --> 00:31:27.980
explore a specific
area of technology

00:31:27.980 --> 00:31:30.680
and uncover opportunity areas.

00:31:30.680 --> 00:31:32.990
Once you've decided
what you want to build,

00:31:32.990 --> 00:31:35.270
and you have a
prototype, methods

00:31:35.270 --> 00:31:38.510
like cognitive walkthroughs,
usability tests,

00:31:38.510 --> 00:31:40.880
or participatory
design exercises

00:31:40.880 --> 00:31:44.340
can help you make
important design decisions.

00:31:44.340 --> 00:31:46.640
And once your product
is out in the market,

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:51.140
methods like log analysis,
diary studies, or surveys

00:31:51.140 --> 00:31:54.290
can help you evaluate
its performance.

00:31:54.290 --> 00:31:58.070
And if you don't have a lot of
time or experience, that's OK.

00:31:58.070 --> 00:32:02.270
Just take a few hours
and talk to a few users.

00:32:02.270 --> 00:32:04.400
Jacob Nielsen of the
Nielsen Norman Group

00:32:04.400 --> 00:32:08.690
found that the best results come
from small affordable studies

00:32:08.690 --> 00:32:10.400
with no more than five users.

00:32:14.130 --> 00:32:17.280
So now, I'd like to
show you how Android

00:32:17.280 --> 00:32:22.210
uses user research to improve
our accessibility offerings.

00:32:22.210 --> 00:32:25.790
Let's take the example of
TalkBack vibration feedback.

00:32:25.790 --> 00:32:27.480
TalkBack, the Google
screen reader,

00:32:27.480 --> 00:32:30.060
uses vibration
feedback by default.

00:32:30.060 --> 00:32:32.250
We knew that some
people turned this off,

00:32:32.250 --> 00:32:33.630
and we wanted to know why.

00:32:33.630 --> 00:32:38.190
Why do some people turn it
off while others leave it on?

00:32:38.190 --> 00:32:40.800
Are there situations
where vibration

00:32:40.800 --> 00:32:45.270
is more or less useful, and
does the pattern or intensity

00:32:45.270 --> 00:32:47.370
of the vibration
make a difference?

00:32:47.370 --> 00:32:50.520
Good research starts with
good research questions.

00:32:53.940 --> 00:32:56.210
Because we were
interested in perceptions

00:32:56.210 --> 00:32:59.940
of vibration feedback, we
started with user interviews.

00:32:59.940 --> 00:33:02.880
We asked screen reader
users questions like,

00:33:02.880 --> 00:33:05.010
do you use vibration feedback?

00:33:05.010 --> 00:33:06.360
Why or why not?

00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:07.950
Have you ever turned it off?

00:33:07.950 --> 00:33:09.150
When did you turn it off?

00:33:09.150 --> 00:33:11.820
And how would you describe
the intensity of vibration

00:33:11.820 --> 00:33:12.990
on your phone?

00:33:12.990 --> 00:33:16.260
Is it too high, too
low, or just right?

00:33:16.260 --> 00:33:18.980
After getting a sense of
the participants' needs,

00:33:18.980 --> 00:33:21.810
we prompted them to
compare vibration feedback

00:33:21.810 --> 00:33:24.610
across a range of
Android phones.

00:33:24.610 --> 00:33:27.910
So these tasks added a usability
component to our study.

00:33:31.620 --> 00:33:34.410
In this research, we
validated a real need

00:33:34.410 --> 00:33:36.060
for vibration feedback.

00:33:36.060 --> 00:33:38.040
We learned that
vibration provides

00:33:38.040 --> 00:33:40.170
valuable navigational
information

00:33:40.170 --> 00:33:42.780
to visually impaired
users, especially

00:33:42.780 --> 00:33:44.670
in noisy environments
when they may not

00:33:44.670 --> 00:33:48.220
be able to hear spoken
feedback on their device.

00:33:48.220 --> 00:33:51.850
We also learned that the more
distinct the vibration pattern,

00:33:51.850 --> 00:33:53.500
the more useful.

00:33:53.500 --> 00:33:56.520
Finally, we learned that
users wanted the ability

00:33:56.520 --> 00:33:59.190
to adjust vibration
intensity according

00:33:59.190 --> 00:34:01.440
to their personal preferences.

00:34:01.440 --> 00:34:04.800
So in Android P, we're
giving up greater control

00:34:04.800 --> 00:34:07.260
to the user over
vibration feedback.

00:34:07.260 --> 00:34:11.850
Anyone will be able to go to
their Accessibility Settings

00:34:11.850 --> 00:34:15.449
and increase, decrease,
or disable vibration,

00:34:15.449 --> 00:34:16.989
and this is just the beginning.

00:34:16.989 --> 00:34:19.710
We will continue to make
improvements in this area

00:34:19.710 --> 00:34:22.060
as we further research.

